  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding customer transaction patterns\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing AML compliance programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Transaction Monitoring\n- Tracking unusual financial activities\n- Detecting potential money laundering patterns\n- Investigating suspicious transactions\n\n5. Staff Training\n- Educating employees about AML regulations\n- Teaching identification of potential money laundering signs\n- Maintaining ongoing compliance awareness\n\n6. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n- Preserving customer identification documents\n- Ensuring records are accessible for potential investigations\n\nFinancial institutions can face significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges, for failing to meet these AML obligations.",
